  m_Name: Mushroom_19_Hollowheart
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Hollowfen.Data.MushroomFieldGuideData
  _id: hollowheart
  _commonName: Hollowheart
  _latinName: Amanita phalloides
  _edibility: 1
  _edibilityLabel: Deadly
  _description: "Sable's seedbook name for the Death Cap (Amanita phalloides) \u2014
    the most lethal mushroom on Earth, blamed for roughly half of all mushroom-poisoning
    deaths worldwide. The old hand named it Hollowheart for how it kills: pleasant
    to eat, then quiet for a day while it hollows the liver from within."
  _idFeatures:
  - Cap olive-green to pale yellow, smooth and slightly sticky when moist
  - White free gills, not attached to the stem
  - White ring (annulus) on the upper stem
  - "Bulbous volva at the base, often hidden in litter \u2014 always brush down to
    check"
  - White spore print
  _habitat: "Mycorrhizal with broadleaf trees \u2014 oak, beech, hornbeam."
  _season: Late summer through autumn
  _lookalikes: Field Mushroom and Horse Mushroom are edible but have pink or brown
    gills, never white, and no volva. Caesar''s Mushroom has an orange cap with yellow
    gills. The volva at the base is the single most important check.
  _notes: 'There is no antidote. Symptoms appear six to twelve hours after eating:
    severe illness, then a deceptive well period of a day or two, then liver and
    kidney failure. By the time you feel sick, the damage is done. Sable''s warning,
    half lost to damp, ends: only once.'
